uvais, the name of several places in various parts of France.","History: Jacques Beauvais <i>dit</i> Saint-Gemme from the Perche region of France is recorded in Montreal, QC, in 1654."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guillaume de Beauvais II was born about 1205, in France, his father, Guillaume De Beauvais, was 21 and his mother, Marguerite De Guerbigny, was 11203. He had at least 1 son with Léonore Crépin."},"et":{"about 1205–":"umbes 1205–Surnud","1205–Male":"1205–Surnud","1210–1282":"1210–1282","1235–1296":"1235–1296","1185–Male":"1185–Surnud","1182–1225":"1182–1225","1205":"1205","1225":"1225","1235":"1235","about 1205":"umbes 1205","1210":"1210","1296":"1296","1185":"1185","1282":"1282","1182":"1182","Beauvais, Oise, Picardie, France":"Beauvais, Oise, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 1205–":"noin 1205–Kuollut","1205–Male":"1205–Kuollut","1210–1282":"1210–1282","1235–1296":"1235–1296","1185–Male":"1185–Kuollut","1182–1225":"1182–1225","1205":"12